\u003Cstrong\u003Eteres major\u003C/strong\u003E muscle. This anatomical landmark is important for clinicians to know, as the brachial artery is commonly used for blood pressure measurements and intravenous access.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eteres minor\u003C/strong\u003E is a rotator cuff muscle located in the shoulder, not directly related to the brachial artery\u0027s course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epectoralis minor\u003C/strong\u003E is a muscle located in the chest, and while it is near the axillary artery, it does not mark the beginning of the brachial artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubscapularis\u003C/strong\u003E is another rotator cuff muscle located on the anterior surface of the scapula, not associated with the brachial artery\u0027s starting point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erhomboid minor\u003C/strong\u003E is a muscle of the upper back, involved in scapular movement, and is not related to the brachial artery\u0027s anatomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The brachial artery begins at the inferior border of the teres major muscle.","Understanding the anatomical landmarks of major arteries is crucial for clinical procedures such as blood pressure measurement and intravenous access."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 